field_data.Sample Name: Folk1, 10 nm IrO2 on 5 nm Ti on glassy carbon
field_data.Removed from vacuum: removed from sputter chamber ~ 2 hours ago

notes: 500 Ohm! 01... very active. 02... Is the cathodic current on the (only one!) sweep down to ~0 V vs RHE H adsorption or IrO2 reduction? Nice RHE calibration, RE_vs_RHE=0.720. 03... everything going well. Activity seems a bit decreased after RHE calibration 05... 1 uA repeated 06... if anything OCV went down 5 mV when introducing O2. OER activity looks identical in He and in O2. Recalibrating HER: Does not look even a little bit similar... OCV in H2 looks the same (or maybe shifted 2 to 3 mV, to 0.717... no, still 0.720), but surface is MUCH less active for HOR. What's up with that? Resistance changed to 0 V at cycle 6, 1:37:31 into EC file 06... Squiggles quickly grow out of control. Put resistor back to 500 Ohm when I realized it might be roughening the electrode surface. Potentiostate IMMEDIATELY regains control. Electrode looks more active afterwards, but the activity is transient. ----- Reshma3B ------- 500 Ohm No contact to RE, fixed by flowing a bit through RE hole, then looks good! 01... CV's look great. Doing a few extra to 0.730 V vs RE (1.45 V vs RHE) to let it stabilize, as activity is increasing from one cycle to the next. As usual, no sign of lattice exchange. Looks stable enough after 8 cycles. Three cycles at 1.425 V vs RHE. Current oscilates a bit after switching to O2 (1:00 in EC, 27500 in MS) ----- Reshma4B ------- 500 Ohm 01... some electrochemical noise on first anodic sweep. And all the anodic sweeps. It's pretty gross. But... Activity matches Reshma4A from 18H28! :) Okay, noise not getting better. Taking a radical step. Pulled sample back by rotating RDE stick hat with pliers. 02... - 03... No success. I'm stuck with this. Best cycle is cycle 2 of 03... This can maybe be plotted nicely (enough) bu just smoothing the current. Noise continues during potential holds, but O2 signal looks nice and square. Activity is no problem, but I don't know if I can get faradaic efficiency out of this data. Will probably have to do it again.
